Constructing objects 

When creating an object, they are separate from other objects. Values held within an object will not be overridden if a new one is created 

When adding another class as an attribute of a class, it does not create new memory, but creates a reference to the existing memory block.  

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Changes in a class that is an attribute of another class will therefore be represented in the parent class.  

Static 

If an attribute is static, it creates a shared space in memory that all objects of that class share. Therefore when it is changed, it is represented across all objects of that class. This is useful when two or more objects need to share information.  

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Static methods can be called without needing an instance of a class. Often called class level methods.  

Using static has advantages such as memory efficiency, global access and object independence. 

Instance fields cannot be accessed through static methods. This can only be done by passing the instance field in as a parameter.   

Scope 

Scope is where a variable you declare can be used. For example, if you create a variable in a method, that variables scope is only in that method. Same applies for declaring i in for loops.  

By having scope, your program becomes far more memory efficient. Once a method is done executing, the variables stored within it no longer exist.  

The same idea applies to objects 

Object destruction 

While an object is alive, it has not gone out of scope.  

Garbage collection - Destruction of objects that are no longer needed (when no longer referenced). It is an automatic process in Java. 

References that are held in a variable are usually dropped when the variable goes out of scope, or when an object reference is set to null.
